// p83 — Tuples stored in collections display and read back
// correctly (v3.25.0).
//
// Long-standing bug: `xs.append((1, "a")); print(xs)` displayed
// `[]` instead of `[(1, "a")]`. The tuple was stored as a raw
// `Tuple*` in the List, and `quirk_opaque_to_string` had no way
// to distinguish it from a `String*` (no runtime tag on the
// struct), so it interpreted the tuple's `data` pointer as a
// String buffer and printed garbage / empty.
//
// Fix is two-piece:
//
//   1. Boxing on store. The Codegen call-arg processor sees a
//      Tuple value flowing into an `Any`-typed extern parameter
//      (List.append's `item: Any`, etc.) and wraps it in an
//      Any-tagged-ANY_TUPLE box via `Core_Primitives_Any_box_tuple`
//      so `quirk_opaque_to_string` can classify it correctly via
//      the tag-range check.
//
//   2. Unboxing on read. The Codegen var-decl path for `p: Tuple
//      = xs.get(0)` now routes the i8* result through
//      `quirk_opaque_to_struct` (new runtime helper) which extracts
//      `Any->ptr` when the value is an Any wrapper and passes it
//      through unchanged when it's a raw struct pointer. Bare
//      bitcast (the previous behaviour) was wrong for Any-wrapped
//      values — it aligned the Any's `tag` field with the target
//      struct's first field and corrupted every subsequent access.
//
// Both halves are required: without (2), itertools.enumerate's
// pre-existing raw-tuple storage shape would have broken on
// `p: Tuple = r.get(0)` (the regression my first attempt hit).
// The opaque-to-struct dispatch handles both shapes transparently.
//
// Same machinery now also makes `v: String = m.get(k)` route
// through `quirk_opaque_to_string` (handles tagged-int / Any /
// raw String shapes — broader than the previous `Any_to_str`
// which only worked on genuine Any* boxes).

xs := List()
xs.append((1, "a"))
xs.append((2, "b"))
xs.append((42, "answer"))

print(xs.length())        // = 3
print(xs)                 // = [(1, a), (2, b), (42, answer)]

// Field access on the unboxed Tuple element.
p: Tuple := xs.__get(0)
print(p.0)                // = 1
print(p.1)                // = a

// And later positions.
last: Tuple := xs.__get(2)
print(last.0)             // = 42
print(last.1)             // = answer
